{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1586268308,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDYxMDQwNjc4Ng==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-610406786"},"message":"I learnt this one-shot read trick from @erthink \nI guess he is a hacker. He says it will trig warning from security software no mention other problems.\nMaybe opertation system leaves some bytes (128bits?) outside the buffer. For example, an AVX load may go across the boundary.\nI would like to hear from  @erthink on the consequence of this technology.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"cd39cff1d03b98b2a39748873893d10f390255ac"},"timestamp":1586269206,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDYxMDQxNTA0NA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-610415044"},"message":"It's known, that saving metadata \"in front of a buffer\" is quite common - i.e. reading there is on many systems OK. Reading data past a buffer is known to sometimes work due to overallocation strategies on many systems.\n\nThe problem is, that both behavior are unpredictable, non-standardized, and not guaranteed (not even on those systems in the situation when it worked once, after some time or update or whatever it'll stop working or even do some harm).\n\nSo I think it's a nice non-default property of a hash function to gain speed, but I don't think it's wise to make it a default for cross-platform hash function.\n\nCurious what @erthink will say.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1586295173,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDYxMDYzMTc0OA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-610631748"},"message":"Good idea, using asan or valgrind.\n\nIn practice it depends on the context, if overflows are allowed. similar to if all accesses are aligned. Normally they are not, but sometimes it makes sense to reserve more to get faster hashes.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597650888,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3NDUxMTYxNQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-674511615"},"message":"In general we don't want to accept oob (out-of-bounds) hashfuncs. I've added asan and now also ubsan recipes, and all hashes violating these should be labelled poor or unsafe, or not accepted at all.\nI've added the asan test to `sanity.sh`\n\npractically such improvements do make sense of course if you can guarantee that the end of tested input buffers never cross a page boundary.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597650888,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlQ29tbWVudEVkaXQ6MzkzNDg1Nzkx"},"target":"b19dd1ce6136bf44f1e563ad6b03aa69a81d2bab8ff577c526d706c07986d3fe","message":"In general we don't want to accept oob (out-of-bounds) hashfuncs. I've added asan and now also ubsan recipes, and all hashes violating these should be labelled **UB** (undefined behaviour), or not accepted at all for oob.\nI've added the asan test to `sanity.sh`\n\npractically such improvements do make sense of course if you can guarantee that the end of tested input buffers never cross a page boundary.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"cd39cff1d03b98b2a39748873893d10f390255ac"},"timestamp":1597581389,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3NDUyMTQxMg==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-674521412"},"message":"Thanks @rurban ! I think this can be closed then. If not, feel free to reopen.","files":null},{"type":4,"author":{"id":"cd39cff1d03b98b2a39748873893d10f390255ac"},"timestamp":1597581389,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDExOkNsb3NlZEV2ZW50MzY1OTI4MzE2OQ=="},"status":2},{"type":4,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597648558,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEzOlJlb3BlbmVkRXZlbnQzNjYwNTEzNzQx"},"status":1},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597648602,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3NDcwNzY5MA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-674707690"},"message":"Documentation of UB problems still missing.\nAdding it now...","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597648602,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlQ29tbWVudEVkaXQ6MzkzNDc4NDQx"},"target":"0593b1b213719c4b2b7980970aa3a61d7cfff610da395f3dabf9e49e02c849e1","message":"Documentation of UB problems still missing.\nAdding it now...\n\nTypical undefined behaviour (**UB**) problems:\n\n* Misaligned\n\n  Many fast word hashes dont check the input buffer for proper word\n  alignment, which will fail with ubsan or Sparc. word being `int32_t` or\n  `int64_t` or even more.\n  On some old RISC hardware this will be a BUS error, you can even let\n  Intel HW generate such a bus error by setting some CPU flag. But generally\n  using misaligned accesses is fine.\n  E.g. mx3, Spooky, mirhash, MUM, fasthash, Murmur3*, Murmur2*, metrohash,\n  Crap8, discohash, beamsplitter, lookup3, fletcher4, fletcher2, FNV2, \n  all sanmayce FNV1a\\_ variants (FNV1a\\_YT, FNV1A\\_Pippip\\_Yurii, FNV1A\\_Totenschiff, ...),\n  fibonacci\n\n  The usual mitigation is to check the buffer alignment either in the caller,\n  provide a pre-processing loop for the misaligned prefix, or copy the whole buffer\n  into a fresh aligned area.\n\n* oob - Out of bounds\n\n  Some hash function assume a padded input buffer which can be\n  accessed past its length up to the word size. This allows for faster\n  loop processing, as no 2nd loop or switch table for the rest is\n  needed, but it requires a cooperative calling enviroment and is as\n  such considered cheating.\n\n* Signed integer overflow\n\n  A simple type error, this hash needs to use unsigned integer types internally, to avoid\n  undefined and inconsistent behaviour.\n  i.e. SuperFastHash: signed integer overflow: -2147483641 + -113 cannot be represented in type 'int'\n\n* shift exponent overflow\n\n  With: FNV1A\\_Pippip\\_Yurii, FNV1A_Totenschiff, pair\\_multiply\\_shift, sumhash32\n  shift exponent 64 is too large for 64-bit type 'long unsigned int'","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597650825,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3NDcyMzMzOQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/117#issuecomment-674723339"},"message":"Done with 5ec69d6ed9b760c02b1f1f635234ba3f7113dd30","files":null},{"type":4,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1597650825,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDExOkNsb3NlZEV2ZW50MzY2MDY0MDAxOA=="},"status":2}]}